'''California State Polytechnic University, Pomona''', or '''Cal Poly Pomona''', is a [[public university]] located in [[Pomona, California|Pomona]], [[California]], [[United States]]. It is one of [[Cal Poly|two polytechnics]] in the 23-member [[California State University]] system.

Cal Poly Pomona began as a satellite campus of the California Polytechnic School (today known as [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]]) in 1938 when a completely equipped school and farm in the city of [[San Dimas, California|San Dimas]] were donated by Charles Voorhis and his son [[Jerry Voorhis]]. The satellite campus grew further in 1949 when a [[Ranch|horse ranch]] in the neighboring city of Pomona, and who had belonged to [[Will Keith Kellogg]], were acquired. Cal Poly Pomona, then known as <U+201C>Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis Unit<U+201D>, and Cal Poly San Luis Obispo continued operations under a unified administrative control until they became independent from each other in 1966. 

Cal Poly Pomona currently offers multiple educational programs in [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona academics|9 academic units]] and enrolls over 22,000 students as of fall 2010. The university is one among a small group of [[Institute of Technology (United States)#Polytechnic Universities|polytechnic universities in the United States]] which tend to be primarily devoted to the instruction of technical arts and applied sciences.

Once known strictly as a commuter school, in recent years Cal Poly Pomona has undertaken an effort to increase its academic standings while also evolving into a more traditional university. The university has raised admissions standards, increased on-campus student residences, built new facilities and expanded [[U.R. Bronco|its undergraduate research opportunities]]. Its sports teams are known as the [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos]] and play in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division II (NCAA)|Division II]] as part of the [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] (CCAA). The Broncos sponsor 10 varsity sports and have won 14 NCAA national championships.

==History==
{{Dablink|See also: [[California Polytechnic State University#History|History of California Polytechnic State University in San Luis Obispo]].<ref group=Note>From 1938 to 1966 the California Polytechnic (Cal Poly) intermittently operated as one institution in up to three different locations: Pomona, San Dimas and San Luis Obispo.</ref>}}
{{Quote box |quote = Let it be the [[Cornell University|Cornell]] of the Pacific... where any person can find instruction in any study. |source = <small>Myron Angel, founder of the California Polytechnic School, San Luis Obispo, CA. January 7, 1899.</small><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=15.}}</ref> |align = right |width = 300px |fontsize = 90% |bgcolor = lightblue |quoted = 1}}
[[File:W.K. Kellogg with Antez (1929).PNG|thumb|right|250px|Cal Poly Pomona stands on the former Arabian horse ranch of cereal magnate [[Will Keith Kellogg|W.K. Kellogg]].]]
Events leading to the foundation of present-day Cal Poly Pomona began with the demise of the Voorhis School for Boys in [[San Dimas, California]] and its acquisition by the [[San Luis Obispo, California|San Luis Obispo]]-based California Polytechnic School in 1938.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=41.}}</ref>

The California Polytechnic School was founded as a [[Vocational education in the United States|vocational]] [[high school]] when California Governor [[Henry Gage]] signed the Polytechnic School Bill on March 8, 1901 after its drafting by school founder Myron Angel.ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=18.}}</ref> Voorhis School, on the other hand, had been established in 1928 as a private vocational school which provided [[Primary education|elementary schooling]] for underprivileged boys and operated under the [[Christianity|Christian]] religious principle, "education coupled with the Kingdom of God".<ref>{{cite web |title= New president takes the reins at Cal Poly Pomona |url= http://www.allbusiness.com/north-america/united-states-california/929276-1.html |work= Inland Empire Business Journal  |accessdate= 2010-01-02}}</ref><ref name="Pflueger 1999 44">{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=44.}}</ref> Its founder Charles B. Voorhis and [[Head teacher|headmaster]] [[Jerry Voorhis]] maintained the school opened throughout the worst years of the [[Great Depression]] but persistent economic pressures forced them to transfer control to Cal Poly in San Luis Obispo in 1938.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=45.}}</ref> Hence, Voorhis School became the Cal Poly-Voorhis Unit and its educational offerings were raised to the same level as Cal Poly SLO.<U+2019>s <U+2013>then a two-year college.<ref name="Cal Poly San Luis Obispo">{{cite web |url= http://www.alumni.calpoly.edu/alumniinfo/university-history.html |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20080616082843/http://www.alumni.calpoly.edu/alumniinfo/university-history.html |archivedate= 2008-06-16 |title= University History |publisher=[[California Polytechnic State University]] | accessdate=2010-02-04}}</ref> The entire horticulture program was moved to the new satellite campus and the two units operated as one institution spanning two locations under the leadership of president Julian McPhee.<ref name="Campus History, Cal Poly San Dimas?">{{cite web| url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~library/specialcollections/history/sandimas.html| title=Cal Poly San Dimas?| first=Allen| last=Ferreira| year=1985| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=2010-01-31}}</ref>

During [[World War II]] most of the student body was called to active duty, enrollment declined and the campus closed in 1943.<ref name="Campus History, Cal Poly San Dimas?"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=51.}}</ref> Reopening after the war, Cal Poly-Voorhis Unit operated in San Dimas until 1956 when it moved to [[Will Keith Kellogg]]<U+2019>s former [[Ranch|horse ranch]] in the neighboring city of [[Pomona, California]].<ref name="CPP History">{{cite web | title= Heritage and History at Cal Poly Pomona  | url= http://www.csupomona.edu/cpp_heritage.php| publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | accessdate=2010-11-11}}</ref> Acknowledging its Kellogg legacy, Cal Poly-Voorhis Unit changed its name to Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis Unit and offered six programs in agriculture.<ref name="CPP History" />  The inaugural class of 1957 at the new campus consisted of 57 students graduating with Bachelor<U+2019>s degrees in a ceremony held at the Rose Garden in Pomona and religious services at Voorhis Chapel in San Dimas.<ref name="Catalog">{{cite web | title= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona - Historical Development | url= http://www.csupomona.edu/~academic/catalog/gen_info/Univ_Admin.pdf| publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | format=PDF | accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=103.}}</ref>  Also in 1957, Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis introduced the [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Engineering|College of Engineering]], the second academic unit after the [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Agriculture|College of Agriculture]].<ref name="csupomona.edu">{{Citation | title = University Ranks Fifth in West, Engineering Program Ninth in Nation by U.S. News & World Report | newspaper = PolyTrends | page = 2 | year = 2003 | url = http://www.csupomona.edu/~advancement/publications/polytrends_fall03.pdf | accessdate = January 31, 2010}}</ref> The [[California Master Plan for Higher Education]] added the two Cal Poly campuses to the new California State College system in 1961 and Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis Unit opened its doors for the first time to 329 female students.<ref name="CPP History" /> President McPhee retired in 1966, and the two Cal Poly split becoming two different and independent universities.  The partnership between the two campuses remains with their involvement in the annual [[Cal Poly Universities Rose Float]].<ref name="Cal Poly San Luis Obispo" /><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|pp=133&ndash;134.}}</ref>

To better reflect its new ties to the State College system, Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis changed its name to <U+201C>California State Polytechnic College, Kellogg-Voorhis<U+201D> in 1966 and became the 16th campus to officially join.<ref name="CPP History" /> Robert C. Kramer assumed presidency of the independent campus in 1966 (second overall as the university recognizes McPhee as its first) and California State Polytechnic College, Kellogg-Voorhis finally adopted its present-day name California State Polytechnic University, Pomona on June 1, 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~library/specialcollections/oralhistory/ |title=Voices From Our Past - Cal Poly Pomona Oral History |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |date=2009-03-18 |accessdate=2010-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/pa/info/milestones.shtml |title=CSU &#124; Public Affairs &#124; Historic Milestones |publisher=[[California State University]] |date=2009-03-18 |accessdate=2010-04-30}}</ref>

In 1998, Cal Poly Pomona received criticism when it planned to grant an honorary degree to [[Robert Mugabe]]. Mugabe<U+2019>s negative humanitarian record as president of [[Zimbabwe]] lead protests from staff, faculty and students ultimately forcing the university to rescind the award.<ref>{{cite news | title= Cal Poly Pomona Chief Is Focus of Campus Contention | url= http://articles.latimes.com/1998/jun/15/local/me-60140| work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=2008-09-02 | first=Kenneth R. | last=Weiss | date=1998-06-15}}</ref>

Cal Poly Pomona underwent further growth in the late 20th and early 21st centuries, with the construction of the [[CLA Building]], academic facilities, expansion to the [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]] and the addition of programs such as the [[Lyle Center for Regenerative Studies]], the [[International Polytechnic High School|I-Poly High School]] and the [[U.R. Bronco]] undergraduate research program. Under president [[J. Michael Ortiz]], Cal Poly Pomona launched its first comprehensive capital campaign in fall of 2008 to increase its permanent endowment.  Nevertheless, the negative economic effects caused by the [[late-2000s recession]] has increased student fees, reduced enrollment availability, eliminated two athletic programs and the introduced a mandatory [[furlough]] calendar for most of its 47,000 employees.<ref>{{cite web | title= CSU Trustees Vote to Raise 2010-11 Fees by 5 Percent | url= http://polycentric.csupomona.edu/news_stories/2010/06/csu-trustees-raise-fees-5percent.html| work= PolyCentric |accessdate=2010-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= California State University Officials Outline Enrollment Cuts and Preview 2010-2011 Budget | url= http://www.calstate.edu/pa/news/2009/enrollment-budget.shtml| publisher= [[California State University]] |accessdate=2010-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Cal Poly Pomona Forced to Drop Men<U+2019>s and Women<U+2019>s Tennis | url= http://www.scta.usta.com/News/steve-2010/CalPoly/| publisher= [[United States Tennis Association]] |accessdate=2010-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Employee Furlough Information | url= http://www.csupomona.edu/~hr/furloughs.shtml| publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=2010-09-11}}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona<U+2019>s financial endowment declined in value from $33.7 million in fiscal year 2007 to $27.6 million in 2009.<ref name="2007 NACUBO">{{cite web | title = All Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2008 Market Value of Endowment Assets with Percentage Change Between 2007 and 2008 Endowment Assets| work = 2008 NACUBO Endowment Study| publisher = National Association of College and University Business Officers | url = http://www.nacubo.org/documents/research/NES2008PublicTable-AllInstitutionsByFY08MarketValue.pdf| format = PDF | accessdate = 2010-09-11}}</ref><ref name="2009 NACUBO">As of June 30, 2009.{{cite web | title = U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2009 Endowment Market Value and Percentage Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2008 to FY 2009| work = 2009 NACUBO-Commonfund Study of Endowments | publisher = National Association of College and University Business Officers | url = http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/research/2009_NCSE_Public_Tables_Endowment_Market_Values.pdf| format = PDF | accessdate = 2010-09-11}}</ref>

===Name===
{{Dablink|See also: [[California State University#Campus naming conventions|Campus naming conventions in the CSU]] and [[California Polytechnic State University#Name]].}}
The campus' office of public affairs recognizes two official names for the university: "California State Polytechnic University, Pomona" and "Cal Poly Pomona".<ref name="Graphic Standard Manual">{{cite news| url= http://www.csupomona.edu/~publicaffairs/graphics/nomenclature.shtml| title=Identity| publisher= Office of Public Affairs at Cal Poly Pomona| accessdate=2010-02-01}}</ref> However, "Cal Poly" has also been used to refer to Cal Poly Pomona, as both itself and [[California Polytechnic State University]] at [[San Luis Obispo, California]] were one institution spanning two locations from 1938 to 1966.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=11.}}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona's office of public affairs recommends not to abbreviate the university's name merely as "Cal Poly".<ref name="Graphic Standard Manual"/> In the years when the [[University of California]] was in charge of Kellogg's donated estate in Pomona (1932<U+2013>1943), the names "University of California, W.K. Kellogg Institute" and "W.K. Kellogg Institute of Animal Husbandry <small>University of California, Pomona</small>", came into use to describe the site.<ref>{{Harvnb|Parkinson|2001|p=213.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Parkinson|2001|p=204.}}</ref> Although Cal Poly Pomona is now part of the [[California State University]], its naming convention does not follow that of most campuses within the system ([[E.g.#exempli gratia|e.g.]] the CSU campus in [[San Diego]] bears the full official name "[[San Diego State University]]" and the CSU campus in [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]] uses the name "[[California State University, Fullerton]]").<ref>{{cite web| title=The New SDSU Graphic Identity System| url=http://advancement.sdsu.edu/marcomm/logo/SDSU_User_Manual_1.3.pdf| format=PDF| work= [[San Diego State University]]| page=4| accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Editorial Style| url= http://www.fullerton.edu/identity/downloads/guidelines/editorial-style.pdf| format=PDF| work= [[California State University, Fullerton]]| page=3| accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> Thus, "Pomona State University" and "California State University, Pomona" are seldom used and not in the university's graphic standard's manual.<ref name="Graphic Standard Manual"/>  Nonetheless, Cal Poly Pomona's [[web page]] is <code><nowiki>http://www.csupomona.edu/</nowiki></code>..

==Campus==
{{wide image-2|CLA Portrait.jpg|700px|Panorama of the [[CLA Building]] at Cal Poly seen from the engineering meadow. The Japanese garden is at the lower left of the image.|75%|right}}

Cal Poly Pomona is situated in [[Pomona, California|Pomona]], a largely suburban city that is part of the [[Los Angeles metropolitan area]]. The city of Pomona is located in the eastern portion of [[Los Angeles County]] and borders the neighboring [[San Bernardino County|county of San Bernardino]] to the east. The university<U+2019>s {{convert|1438|acre|km2|sp=us}} campus<ref name="Physical Cal Poly Pomona">{{cite web  |url= http://www.csupomona.edu/~jskoga/physicalcalpoly/ |title= The Physical Cal Poly Pomona |author= James S. Koga |publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate= 2008-08-27}}</ref> make it the second largest in the [[California State University]] system,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aaiep.org/schools/show/189/cal_poly_english_language_institute |title=Cal Poly English Language Institute |publisher=American Association of Intensive English Programs |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> a figure which includes various facilities scattered throughout [[Southern California]] such as a {{convert|53|acre|m2|sing=on}} ranch in [[Santa Paula, California]], {{convert|25|acre|m2|sing=on}} campus at the former Spadra Landfill (now known as "Spadra Ranch"),<ref name="Facilities">{{cite web | url= http://www.csupomona.edu/~plantsci/facilities.shtml | title=Department Facilities | publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| accessdate=2008-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lacsd.org/about/solid_waste_facilities/spadra/default.asp | title=Spadra Landfill (Post Closure Activities) | publisher=Sanitation Districts of Los Angeles County | accessdate=2011-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Neutra VDL Studio and Residences]] in [[West Los Angeles]]. In addition, the main Pomona campus is home to a 31-hectare (0.31 km2) [[Nature reserve|ecological reserve]] known as the Voorhis Ecological Reserve.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~jcclark/classes/bot343/project1.html| title=Project: Flora of Cal Poly Pomona| last=Clark| first= Curtis| publisher=California State polytechnic University, Pomona| year=2005| accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref>

Although part of the [[Los Angeles metropolitan area]], the university is in close proximity to two other large metropolitan and culturally-defined regions, the [[Inland Empire (California)|Inland Empire]] and [[Orange County, California|Orange County]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkinguge.com/research/inland-empire-insights.php| title=Inland Empire Insights| work=Wilkin Guge Marketing| year=2008| accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> The university has a tier 1 area, defined as an geographical admissions region surrounding the campus, roughly bounded by the [[San Gabriel Mountains]] to the north, the city of [[Chino Hills]] to the south, [[Interstate 605]] to the east, and [[Interstate 15]] to the west.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.insidesocal.com/educationnow/2010/02/cal-poly-requiring-certain-fre.html |title= Department Facilities |publisher= [[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]] |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona's campus buildings vary in age and style from the [[Mission Revival Style architecture|Mission Revival]] Kellogg Horse Stables and the Kellogg House (suggesting the [[Spanish architecture#Spanish Colonial architecture|Spanish colonial architectural heritage]] of [[Southern California]]) built in the 1920s; the modernist box-like portion of [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona, Library|the library]] completed in 1969; to contemporary dormitories, engineering, science and library-expansion facilities completed in the early 21st century.{{sfn|CPSUSLO|2001|p=68}}

Leisure and recreational locations include a [[rose garden]] which dates back to the Kellogg horse ranch years; the Kellogg House designed by Los Angeles-based architects Charles Gibbs Adams, [[Myron Hunt]] and Harold Coulson Chambers in the 1920s; and a {{convert|1.3|acre|m2}} [[Japanese garden]] built in 2003 and designed by [[Takeo Uesugi]].<ref name="UW Arch. Database">{{cite web| url= https://digital.lib.washington.edu/architect/structures/3836/| title=Kellogg, W.K., Ranch House, Pomona, CA| publisher=[[University of Washington]]| accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jgarden.org/gardens.asp?ID=642| title=George and Sakaye Aratani Japanese Garden at Cal Poly Pomona| last=Cheetham| first=Robert |publisher=Japanese Garden Research Network, Inc.| accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> Kellogg<U+2019>s House features grounds which were initially landscaped by Charles Gibbs Adams but were later completed by [[Florence Yoch & Lucile Council]].<ref name="UW Arch. Database" /><ref name="US NEWS"/> Cal Poly Pomona's George and Sakaye Aratani Japanese Garden is one among four under management by institutions of higher education in the County of Los Angeles, the other being the Earl Burns Miller Japanese garden at [[California State University, Long Beach|Cal State Long Beach]], the Hannah Carter Japanese garden at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]], and the Shinwa-En Garden at [[California State University, Dominguez Hills|Cal State Dominguez Hills]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la.us.emb-japan.go.jp/e_web/e_m06_29.htm |title=Japanese Gardens in Southern California and Arizona |publisher=Consulate General of Japan in Los Angeles |accessdate=2011-03-31}}</ref> At the center of the campus and atop Horsehill are the buildings comprising the [[Collins College of Hospitality Management]] and Kellogg West, a hotel and conference center and home of the student/faculty-run Restaurant at Kellogg Ranch.  At the north edge of the campus is the Voorhis Ecological Reserve, which serves as a [[wildlife corridor]] containing [[Coastal Sage Scrub]] and [[Quercus agrifolia|Coast Live Oak]] trees among others.  Contrasting some of these architecturally prominent facilities, there are various [[portable building]]s on campus which are used to accommodate the growing enrollment of recent decades. Cal Poly Pomona operates the [[International Polytechnic High School]], a college preparatory high school housed entirely in portable buildings which stand on what used to be a parking lot. As of June 2008, [[financial audit]]or [[KPMG]] valued Cal Poly Pomona's [[capital asset]]s at $307.9 million [[United States dollar|US Dollars]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.csupomona.edu/~fas/docs/0708_financial_statements.pdf|title= Financial Statements| date=2008-06-30| work=[[KPMG]]| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| pages=6<U+2013>43| format=PDF| accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>

Cal Poly Pomona's dominant landmark is a [[futurist]]-style administrative facility known as the [[CLA Building]] which was designed by [[Antoine Predock]] and opened in 1993. The building<U+2019>s peculiar shape (standing out by a triangular-shaped <U+201C>skyroom<U+201D> atop its eight-story tower <ref>{{cite web|url=http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/iconic-cal-poly-pomona-building-poses-earthquake-hazard |title=Iconic Cal Poly Pomona building poses earthquake hazard |author=Erica Perez |date=March 23, 2010 |publisher=[[California Watch]] |accessdate=22 August 2010}}</ref>) has become a symbol of the university; in addition, its close location to film studios based in the [[Hollywood]] borough of Los Angeles have prompted its inclusion in motion pictures such as ''[[Gattacca]]'' and ''[[Impostor (film)|Impostor]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~polycentric/campus_news/123101-imposter.shtml|title=CLA Building Gets Big Screen Treatment as Dimension Films<U+2019> <U+201C>Impostor<U+201D> Hits Theaters | date=2001-12-31 | work=polycentric | accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref>

===Academic and research facilities===
The [[W. K. Kellogg Arabian Horse Center]] is an academic and research facility serving one of the 22 terms and conditions to the donation of the Kellogg ranch by maintaining Kellogg<U+2019>s purebred [[Arabian horse]]s and their breeding program. Another academic facility highlighting the Kellogg legacy is the Horse Stables (also known as University Plaza) which contains a small research library specializing in equine studies along with offices for student services and various campus organizations.

Conceived in 1995 by then university president, Bob H. Suzuki, and initially financed by [[NASA]] and the [[Economic Development Administration]], the Innovation Village is a {{convert|65|acre|m2|adj=on}} public/private partnership research and business facility at the southern edge of the campus. Major tenants include the [[American Red Cross]], [[Southern California Edison]], and the [[NASA]] Commercialization Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.innovationvillage.org/generalinfo.aspx|title=General Information|publisher= Innovation Village|accessdate= 2011-03-03}}</ref> The project is currently at the halfway mark of building and leasing {{convert|1000000|sqft|m2}} of the projected total building space. Once complete, it is estimated that the project would employ 2000 to 3000 people and provide half a billion dollars of economic benefits to the local, regional and state economies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.labusinessjournal.com/news/2005/dec/19/innovation-park-puts-cal-poly-pomona-on-biotech/|title=Innovation Park Puts Cal Poly Pomona on Biotech Map|work=[[Los Angeles Business Journal]]|accessdate=2011-03-03}}</ref>

===Campus sustainability and transportation===
The university has actively sought to reduce carbon emissions and energy usage on campus. In November 2007, Cal Poly Pomona became a signatory member of the [[Campus Carbon Neutrality#American College and University Presidents' Climate Commitment|American College & University Presidents Climate Commitment]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://acupcc.aashe.org/ip/195/ |title= Implementation Profile for California State Polytechnic University-Pomona |month= July, 13 |year= 2009 |publisher= [[Campus Carbon Neutrality#The Association for the Advancement of Sustainability in Higher Education|Association for the Advancement of Sustainability in Higher Education]] |accessdate= 2010-08-22}}</ref> Among other things, this committed the university to ensure that within one year, it would purchase or produce at least 15% of the institution's electric consumption from [[Renewable resource|renewable sources]]. The university, along with other members in the CSU, is also a member of the [[California Climate Action Registry]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.climateregistry.org/about/members.html |title= Members |month= December, 15 |year= 2009 |publisher= [[California Climate Action Registry]] |accessdate= 2010-08-22}}</ref> and lists on ''[[The Princeton Review]]'s'' ''Guide to 286 Green Colleges''.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.princetonreview.com/green-schools-full-list.aspx |title= Members |year= 2010 |publisher= [[The Princeton Review]] |accessdate= 2010-08-22}}</ref>

Cal Poly Pomona's institute for sustainability education is the [[Lyle Center for Regenerative Studies]]. The center was built adjacent to an old landfill and conducts research in the areas of sustainable technology and agriculture. As an example of [[Cradle to Cradle Design]], it uses solar-powered dormitories, aquaculture ponds, and organic gardens while providing an environmentally-sustainable housing accommodation for 22 graduate students. The center is part of Agriscapes, a {{convert|40|acre|m2|adj=on}} research project that showcases environmental and agricultural sustainable practices including methods to grow food, conserve water and energy and recycle urban waste. Agriscapes is home of the Farm Store at Kellogg Ranch which sells locally and campus grown foods and products.  The Cal Poly Pomona campus also contains a rainforest greenhouse, a California [[ethnobotany]] garden, and an aquatic biology center collectively known as BioTrek, which provides environmental education to all academic levels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csupomona.edu/~biotrek/|title=About BioTrek|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=2011-03-04}}</ref>

The entire campus community is served by a free campus shuttle system known as "Bronco Express". The shuttle system comprises 3 lines and is run by the office of Parking & Transportation Services (PTS).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsa.csupomona.edu/parking/maps.asp |title=Bronco Express Shuttle Map|publisher=Dsa.csupomona.edu |date=2009-09-24 |accessdate=2010-04-30}}</ref> In addition, PTS also offers a shuttle service known as "BroncoLink" which provides both students and faculty a direct connection from the Pomona North and Downtown Pomona [[Metrolink (Southern California)|Metrolink]] stations to the [[CLA Building]].<ref name="Rideshare Home">{{cite web|url=http://www.dsa.csupomona.edu/parking/rideshare.asp?nfid=3863 |title=Rideshare Home |publisher=Dsa.csupomona.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-04-30}}</ref>

===Seismic risks and other challenges of campus development===
Although it's believed that the San Jose Fault runs through campus, and geotechnical investigations have been conducted, there is uncertainty regarding its precise [[Fault_(geology)#Fault_types|type]] and location. The CSU Seismic Review Board has classified several buildings on campus as some of the most seismically hazardous in the university system.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pazos|first=Celia S|coauthors=Potter, Hannah; and Polet, Jascha|title=Gravity Profiles across the San Jose Fault on Cal Poly Pomona campus|journal=Abstracts with Programs|publisher=[[Geological Society of America]]|volume=43|issue=2|pages=88|url=http://gsa.confex.com/gsa/2011RM/finalprogram/abstract_187399.htm|accessdate=2011-04-09}}</ref> The CLA Building suffers from structural flaws, most notably, water intrusion. In 2005, the university filed a lawsuit against a contractor, for which it was compensated $13.3 million in an out-of-court [[Settlement (litigation)|settlement]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archrecord.construction.com/news/daily/archives/2010/09/100927predock_cla_building.asp|title=Antoine Predock<U+2019>s CLA Building in California May Be Demolished|last=Hill|first=David|date=2010-09-27|work=[[Architectural Record]]|accessdate=2011-03-04}}</ref> Amid these concerns, on September 2010, the CSU Board of Trustees approved a proposal to have the building razed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://polycentric.csupomona.edu/news_stories/2010/09/csu-proposal-replace-cla.html|title=CSU Approves Proposal to Replace CLA|date=2010-09-22|work=polycentric|accessdate=2011-03-04}}</ref>

[[Hideo Sasaki]]'s architectural firm ''Sasaki Associates, Inc.'' found in the February 2010 [[Comprehensive planning|master plan]] that the campus's [[seismic risk]], uneven terrain, lack of parking spaces, small classrooms, and pedestrian-unfriendly roads are major constrains for future campus development. It also indicated the lack of identity, an undefined sense of arrival, and a desire to build a stronger on-campus community, among others, as recurrent themes among campus's users. Nonetheless, the firm highlights campus ethnic diversity, its location-climate, and the natural beauty of campus, among others, as positive aspects of the physical campus as well as the campus life experience.<ref>{{cite web| title=Cal Poly Pomona Campus Masterplan Forum| url=http://projects.sasaki.com/calpolypomona/Documents/CampusForumVision_002.pdf| format=PDF| work= Sasaki Associates, Inc.| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| date=2010-02-11| pages=3<U+2013>6| accessdate=2011-03-31}}</ref>

==Organization and administration==
