Cal Poly Pomona is one of [[Cal Poly|two polytechnics]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Gerth|2010|p=3.}}</ref> in the 23-member [[California State University]] system.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.calstate.edu/search_find/campus.shtml| title=Campus Homepages| publisher=California State University| accessdate=2010-02-01}}</ref> The CSU system is governed by a 25-member [[board of trustees]], including one faculty trustee, one alumni trustee, and two student trustees, and has authority over curricular development, campus planning, and fiscal management.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.calstate.edu/BOT/ |title=Board of Trustees |publisher=The California State University |accessdate=2010-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/bot/overview.shtml |title=Overview - Board of Trustees |publisher=The California State University |accessdate=2010-01-30}}</ref> The university system is currently governed by Chancellor [[Charles B. Reed]], who assumed the office in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/executive/ |title=Chancellor |publisher=The California State University |accessdate=2010-01-30}}</ref>

The chief executive of the Cal Poly Pomona campus is President [[J. Michael Ortiz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~president/ |title=Office of the President| publisher=The California State University|accessdate=2010-01-30}}</ref> Ortiz's compensation for fiscal year 2008-2009 was $292,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/PA/info/salaryfs.doc| title=CSU Executive Compensation Information| publisher=The California State University| accessdate=2010-01-30}}</ref> 

Cal Poly Pomona is a member of the [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities|American Association of State Colleges and Universities (AASCU)]]<ref name="American Association of State Colleges and Universities">{{cite news| title=Members: C, by State| url= http://www.aascu.org/association/members/c.htm| work= [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities]]| accessdate=2008-08-26}}</ref>

===University Educational Trust (UET)===
The University Educational Trust (UET) is a [[501(c)(3)#501(c)(3)|501 (c)(3)]] tax-exempt organization serving as a source of external fund-raising, funds-management and revenue-distribution at Cal Poly Pomona. With diminishing state support in recent years, the university has become not fully state-supported, but rather, state-assisted.<ref>{{cite web | title=New Territory: Cal Poly Pomona Launches Bold Fundraising Campaign | url=http://campaign.csupomona.edu/2010/11/cal-poly-pomona-launches-bold-fundraising-campaign.html | publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | date=November 4, 2010 | accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref> UET oversees Cal Poly Pomona's endowment and generates resources with help of public and private partners to complement state-support and is recognized by the [[Calstate#Board of Trustees|CSU Board of Trustees]] as a Title V auxiliary organization.<ref>{{cite web | title=Cal Poly Pomona University Educational Trust (UET) - Welcome | url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~uet/index.shtml | publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref> Its member has a total capcity for up to 35 members and currently include 4 officers, 18 community representatives, and 5 university representatives.<ref>{{cite web | title=Cal Poly Pomona University Educational Trust (UET) - Membership Roster | url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~uet/members.shtml | publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref> The board of directors is composed of the university president who acts as an ex-officio voting director and who appoints one ex-officio executive director, one faculty member, one student member, and either the vice president for administrative affairs or the chief financial officer. All of the appointed voting directors serve one, two, or three-year terms and one-year terms thereafter as determined by the university president. Other voting directors are elected by majority votes of present voting directors and serve three year terms and may be re-elected for as many additional three year terms as possible.<ref>{{cite web | title=Cal Poly Pomona University Educational Trust (UET) - UET Bylaws | url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~uet/bylaws.shtml | publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref>

===Endowment===
Cal Poly Pomona's [[financial endowment]] was valued at $32.4 million on June 30, 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~annualreport/uet.shtml | title=Annual Report 2009-10 | year=2010 | publisher=Office of Public Affairs at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=2010-12-08}}</ref> In fall 2010, Cal Poly Pomona embarked on its first comprehensive fundraising campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polycentric.csupomona.edu/news_stories/2010/09/cal-poly-pomona-sets-150-million-fundraising-goal.html|title=Cal Poly Pomona Sets $150 Million Fundraising Goal|year=2010|publisher=Office of Public Affairs at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=2010-12-08}}</ref> Early major donors helped raise more than half of the campaign's goal of $150 million before its formal launch. They included an anonymous benefactor who pledged $12 million,<ref>{{Cite episode |title= Anonymous $12 million gift to Cal Poly Pomona |url= http://www.scpr.org/news/2009/09/03/anonymous-12-million-gift-cal-poly-pomona/ |credits= Cheryl Devall |network= Southern California Public Radio| station= 89.3 KPCC |city= Pasadena| airdate= 2009-09-03}}</ref> and $2 million from 1980 alumni Mickey and Lee Segal.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mickey and Lee Segal Pledge $2 Million to Cal Poly Pomona |url= http://blogs.dailybulletin.com/educationnow/2010/06/mickey-and-lee-segal-pledge-2.html |credits= Canan Tasci |publisher= Inland Valley Daily Bulletin | accessdate= 2010-12-08}}</ref> Just before the campaign launch, on July 26, 2010, the [[W. K. Kellogg Foundation]] awarded a $42 million challenge grant to the university to increase educational access to underrepresented communities, making it the largest cash gift in the history of the [[California State University|CSU system]].<ref>{{Cite press release| title = Cal Poly Pomona Benefits from Unprecedented Gift from W.K. Kellogg Foundation| publisher = [[W. K. Kellogg Foundation]]| date = July 26, 2010| url = http://www.wkkf.org/news/Articles/2010/07/Cal-Poly-Benefits-from-Unprecedented-Gift-from-WKKF.aspx| accessdate = July 26, 2010}}</ref> On February 28, 2011, [[Panda Express]] founders Andrew and Peggy Cherng announced a $2.5 million pledge to Cal Poly Pomona's [[Collins College of Hospitality Management]].<ref>{{Cite press release| title = Panda founders pledge $2.5 million to Cal Poly Pomona | publisher = Pasadena Star-News|date = February 28, 2011|url = http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/business/ci_17504510|accessdate = March 3, 2011}}</ref>

==Academics==
{{Main|California State Polytechnic University, Pomona academics}}
[[Image:Cal Poly Library Entrance.jpg|thumb|right|400px|The main entrance of the [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library|library]] following the renovation.]]

Cal Poly Pomona's academic offerings have evolved throughout the years. Prior to the ownership shift to Cal Poly SLO in 1938, the Voorhis School for Boys in San Dimas had been providing educational offerings in "music, bookkeeping, agriculture, library work, carpentry, nature study, machine shop, and printing" coupled with [[Christian]] religious fundamentals to an all-men student body comprising poor, underage boys.<ref name="Pflueger 1999 44"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=42.}}</ref> In 1938, the campus became the agricultural branch of Cal Poly SLO when a small staff was transfer from San Luis Obispo along with group of agricultural inspection students.<ref>{{Harvnb|Kennedy|2001|p=23.}}</ref> Thus, Cal Poly Pomona (then just Cal Poly) began offering [[Associate's degree]]s in 1938 and [[Bachelor's degree]]s in 1940 when, despite legislative opposition from pro-[[University of California]] members in [[Sacramento]], president Julian McPhee asked allied members Armistead B. Carter and Daniel C. Murphy to introduce the bill when two opposing members were not present to vote.<ref>{{Harvnb|Kennedy|2001|p=24.}}</ref> Following the governance breakup with the San Luis Obispo in 1966, and as outlined by the 1960 [[California Master Plan for Higher Education]], Cal Poly Pomona continued "offer[ing] undergraduate and graduate instruction through the master's degree in the liberal arts and sciences and professional education, including teacher education."<ref name="Master Plan">{{cite news | title=California State University mission | url=http://www.ucop.edu/acadinit/mastplan/csumission.htm| work= University of California <U+2014> Office of the President | accessdate=2010-04-25}}</ref> Currently, Cal Poly Pomona promotes a "learn by doing" philosophy, where an essential part of the curriculum is hands-on application of knowledge.<ref name="Cal Poly Pomona">{{cite news| title=University Vision and Identity Initiative| url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~alumni/docs/focus/meeting/University%20Vision%20and%20Identity%20Presentation.pdf| format=PDF| work= University Advancement Division at Cal Poly Pomona| page=7| accessdate=2008-08-26}}</ref>

[[Merriam-Webster]] mentions that "polytechnic" is a word first used in 1801 derived from the [[French language|French]] ''[http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/polytechnique polytechnique]'' which contains the [[Greek language|Greek]]-[[Root (linguistics)|roots]] "poly" (''[[English language|English]]:many'') and "techn<U+0113>" (''art''). Thus, Merriam-Webster defines "polytechnic" as, "relating to or devoted to instruction in many technical arts or applied sciences".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/polytechnic | title=Polytechnic - Definition and More from the Free Merriam-Webster Dictionary | work=[[Merriam-Webster]]| accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona's polytechnic approach, and learn-by-doing philosophy, encourages students in all programs to get real-world experience and skills necessary to join the workforce upon graduation.<ref name="Polytechnic Approach">{{cite web| title= Polytechnic Approach| url= http://www.dsa.csupomona.edu/visitors/files/polytechniclbd_153.pdf| format=PDF  publisher= Cal Poly Pomona| accessdate= 2008-08-19}}</ref>

In addition, the university is among six other institutions of higher education in California that have been designated a "Center of Academic Excellence" by the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] and the [[National Security Agency]] (NSA).
<ref>{{cite web| title= Student Competition Tests Cyber Security Skills| url= http://campustechnology.com/articles/2009/03/27/student-competition-tests-cyber-security-skills.aspx| last=Schaffhauser |first=Dian |work= Campus Technology | date=2009-03-27 | date=2011-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Centers of Academic Excellence - Institutions | url= http://www.nsa.gov/ia/academic_outreach/nat_cae/institutions.shtml#ca| work= [[National Security Agency]] | accessdate=2009-04-19}}</ref> and a "University of Excellence" according to the [[National Association of State Universities and Land-Grant Colleges]].<ref name="National Association of State Universities and Land-Grant Colleges">{{cite news | title=Universities of Excellence | url= http://www.aplu.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=470&srcid=236| work= [[National Association of State Universities and Land-Grant Colleges]] | accessdate=2009-04-26}}</ref> While all majors are encouraged to participate in [[Cooperative education|co-op]] opportunities and [[Internship#United_States|internships]], all students must do a senior research project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hands-on Activities|url= http://www.csupomona.edu/~cosl/hands-on.html|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=2011-04-09}}</ref> 

The {{convert|300000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]] serves "as the central intellectual and cultural resource of the campus community" and contains over 3 million items and serves as an important center for academic research.<ref>{{cite news | title=University Library Briefing Book Detail | url= http://www.csupomona.edu/~library/about/briefing_book_detail.html| work= [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]]| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> Built in 1969 for $4.2 million, the library underwent a major renovation and expansion completed in the summer of 2008 at a cost of over $46 million dollars.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=160.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~fpm/planning/projects/library_addition.html|title= University Library Addition & Renovation, Phase 1 |publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate= 2008-09-06}}</ref> The library participates in the [[Online Computer Library Center]] (OCLC) Enhance program which allows it to correct or add information to bibliographic records in [[WorldCat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oclc.org/us/en/worldcat/catalog/quality/enhance/default.htm#enhance|title= OCLC Enhance participants  |publisher= [[Online Computer Library Center]]|accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref>

===Rankings===
{{Details|California State Polytechnic University, Pomona academics#Rankings|Cal Poly Pomona's rankings by colleges and departments}}
{{Infobox US university ranking
| Forbes                 = 415
| USNWR_REG              = 32 ([[Western United States|West]])
| Wamo_MASTERSU          = 328}}
[[File:Cal Poly Pomona Winter.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Cal Poly Pomona's [[CLA Building]] with the [[San Gabriel Mountains]] range in the background]]
Cal Poly Pomona ranks 7th among public [[Western United States|Western]] Colleges in ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'s'' 2011 issue of "America's Best Colleges", and 32nd when the category includes both private and public universities.<ref name="US NEWS">{{cite web | title= Best Colleges 2010 | url= http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/pomona-ca/cal-poly-pomona-1144| work= U.S. News & World Report | accessdate=2010-04-25}}</ref> ''U.S. News & World Report'' also ranks Cal Poly Pomona as 4th in ethnic diversity, 8th in least student indebtedness at graduation, 8th in most international students, 6th in lowest acceptance rate, 4th in freshmen retention rate, and 10th in highest graduation rate for public Western colleges.<ref name="US NEWS"/> The report also listed Cal Poly Pomona as 45th in economic diversity, and 59th awarding need-based aid for both private and public universities in the West.

In the academic year 2009/2010 Cal Poly Pomona featured on ''[[Forbes|Forbes magazine]]'' list of "America's Best Colleges" among the 600 best public and private universities in the nation at number 365.<ref>{{cite news | title= America's Best Colleges | http://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/94/colleges-09_California-State-Polytechnic-University-Pomona_94056.html| work= ''[[Forbes|Forbes magazine]]'' | accessdate=2011-04-09 | date=2009-08-05}}</ref>  In the 2010 "PayScale College Salary Report" conducted by ''[[Payscale.com]]'', Cal Poly Pomona ranked 13th among public universities in the country with graduate's starting median salary of $48,500 and a mid-career median salary of $93,300.<ref>{{cite news | title=Top State Universities By Salary Potential | url= http://www.payscale.com/best-colleges/top-state-universities.asp| work= PayScale, Inc. | accessdate=2010-12-21}}</ref>

===Admissions===
