[[File:Student suites at Cal Poly Pomona.png|left|thumb|Residential suites]]

With an on-campus housing capacity of 3,600 students, Cal Poly Pomona has the fifth largest housing system in the [[California State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpp4me.csupomona.edu/|title= Future Students |accessdate=2010-12-05 |work=Cal Poly Pomona}}</ref> There are three  [[dormitory|residential]] styles on the Pomona campus. The oldest housing facilities consist of six residential halls located on University Drive. The four older red-brick halls are named ''Alamitos'', ''Aliso'', ''Encinitas'', and ''Montecito'', each providing accommodation for up to 212 residents.  The other two housing halls (''Cedritos'' and ''Palmitas'') were the result of later housing development and each has room to accommodate up to 185 residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsa.csupomona.edu/uhs/res_halls_desc.asp|title= Residence hall descriptions|accessdate=2008-09-15|work=University Housing Services at Cal Poly Pomona}}</ref> The two newest residential complexes are the ''Village'' and the ''Suites'' which offer apartment-style living to non-freshman students. The ''Residence Halls'' and the ''Suites'' are managed by the Division of Student Affairs, whereas the ''Village'' is managed by the Cal Poly Pomona Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://foundation.csupomona.edu/village/|title=University Village|work=University Village at Cal Poly Pomona|publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Foundation|accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref> Currently about 52% of first-year students and 12% of all undergraduates live in college housing.<ref name="IRAR common data set"/>

While the ''Village''  ''Suites'' are the product of more recent on-campus residential developments. Phase I of the construction of the suites, housing 420 students, completed in 2004 and a second phase is set to open in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~fpm/planning/projects/residential_suites.html |title= Residential Suites, Phase I |accessdate=2008-09-15 |work= Cal Poly Pomona}}</ref> The total on-campus enrollment is 3,200 (as of 2009),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csupomona.edu/future_students.php |title=Cal Poly Pomona |publisher=Csupomona.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-04-30}}</ref> but will grow to over 3,822 after the Phase II of the Residential Suites are completely opened in summer 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~fpm/planning/projects/residential_suites_ph2.html |title=Cal Poly Pomona |publisher=Csupomona.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-04-30}}</ref> making it one of the largest student housing programs in the California State University system.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~publicaffairs/publications/pocketfacts2008.pdf | format=PDF | title= Pocket Facts 2008 | accessdate=2011-03-27 | work=Office of Public Affairs at California State Polytechnic Univeristy, Pomona}}</ref>

In an effort to reduce commuting and raise academic performance and retention, starting on the 2010-2011 academic year, freshmen from outside the Tier 1 Local Admissions area (the area roughly bounded by the San Gabriel Mountains and Chino Hills to the north and south and the 15 and 605 freeways to the east and west), will be required to live on campus.<ref name="President message - Feb 22, 2010"/>

===Bronco Student Center===
{{Main|Bronco Student Center}}

[[Image:Bronco Student Center.jpg|right|thumb|The [[Bronco Student Center]]]]

The Bronco Student Center is a student activity center for meetings, conferences, meals, recreation, and shopping for students and alumni on the campus of Cal Poly Pomona in Pomona, California. This is where ASI student government offices are located, as well as other various student run departments like facilities and operations, Recreation, Programming and Marketing (RPM), Business Services, Games Room Etc. (GRE).

===Campus media===
Campus events are covered by the [[student newspaper]], the ''[[The Poly Post|Poly Post]]''. The Bronco Sports Show is a quarterly television broadcast capturing the highlights and statistics from Bronco Athletics along with other featured events around the campus. ''PolyCentric''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polycentric.csupomona.edu |title=PolyCentric &#124; Cal Poly Pomona |publisher=Polycentric.csupomona.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-04-30}}</ref> is the university's official online magazine. PolyCentric features news, announcements of campus events, spotlights on various departments, and resources for faculty and staff. A web site also provides a comprehensive archival search for past articles and photos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polycentric.csupomona.edu/guide/polycentric-archives.html|title=polycentric Cal Poly Pomona Archives|publisher=Polycentric.csupomona.edu|accessdate=2011-04-09}}</ref>

===Bronco Pep Band===
{{Main|Bronco Pep Band}}

The Bronco Pep Band is a student-run band at Cal Poly Pomona. The band is a group within the [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos|athletic department]]. It follows the tradition of other student-run bands in the sense that it focuses on its members individuality. The band attends athletic events during the year to encourage the school's athletic teams and audience support/involvement. The pep band is entirely voluntary and all students at Cal Poly Pomona or anyone else in the area are free to join.

===Greek life===
Greek Life at Cal Poly Pomona consists of 18 fraternities and 11 sororities governed by the Greek Council. From the total male [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] population, 2% are enrolled in fraternities and 1% of women in soroties respectively. [[Phi Kappa Tau]], [[Sigma Chi]] and [[Sigma Nu]] are three fraternities with off-campus chapter houses.<ref name="College Prowler-Greek Life">{{cite web|url=http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/greek-life/|title=Cal Poly Pomona - Greek Life|publisher=[[College Prowler]]|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsa.csupomona.edu/osl/greeklife/default.asp|title=Welcome to Greek Life at Cal Poly Pomona|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=2011-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sigmanupomona.com/chapter-history|title=Chapter History|publisher=Sigma Nu Fraternity|accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref>

===Rose Parade float===
{{Main|Cal Poly Universities Rose Float}}
Cal Poly Pomona together with [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]] has participated in the [[Tournament of Roses Parade|Tournament of Roses parade]] since 1949; winning the Award of Merit in their first year. In the period from 1949<U+2013>2005, the floats have won 44 awards. This joint program is one of the longest consecutive running self-built entries in the parade, as well as the only "self built" floats designed and constructed entirely by students year-round on both campuses. The Rose Float tradition continues today and marks the partnership between the two Cal Poly campuses.

==Athletics==
{{Main|Cal Poly Pomona Broncos}}

===Voorhis Vikings===
Before the university moved from San Dimas to Pomona, the college had a handful of athletic teams named the '''"Voorhis Vikings"'''. They were composed mostly of homeless and orphaned boys of all races who were cared for at the Voorhis School during the ten-year period it operated.<ref>{{cite web | title=Special Collections & University Archives-Voorhis Vikings | url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~library/specialcollections/voorhis/vikings/index.html  | work= University Library at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| accessdate=2010-04-26}}</ref> Despite this historical background, the university's current athletic programs are named the Broncos.

===Cal Poly Pomona Broncos===
Cal Poly Pomona [[varsity team]]s compete in the [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] of [[Division II (NCAA)|NCAA Division II]]. Teams are known as the [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos]] and field 10 sports for men and women for the [[autumn|fall]], winter, and spring quarters.

{|  style="text-align:left; float:center; font-size:85%; margin-left:2em; margin:auto;"  class="wikitable"
|+ ''Athletic teams''<ref>{{cite web | title=Bronco Sports Teams | url=http://dsa.csupomona.edu/athletics/teams.asp | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080709050826/http://dsa.csupomona.edu/athletics/teams.asp | archivedate=2008-07-09  | work= [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos|Athletics Division at Cal Poly Pomona]]| accessdate=2008-09-14}}</ref>
! !! Mens !! Womens 
